subsection.p:
 Standard Symbols. Sets that are frequently encountered are usually given symbols that are reserved for them alone. For example, since we will be
referring to the positive integers throughout this book, we will use the symbol \mathbb{P} instead of writing \{1, 2, 3, \ldots \}. A few
of the other sets of numbers that we will use frequently are:


\mathbb{P}the positive integers\mathbb{P}: the positive integers, \{1, 2, 3, 4, \ldots \}


\mathbb{N}the natural numbers\mathbb{N}: the natural numbers, \{0, 1, 2, 3, \ldots \}


\mathbb{Z}the integers\mathbb{Z}: the integers, \{\ldots , -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3,\ldots \}


\mathbb{Q}the rational numbers\mathbb{Q}: the rational numbers


\mathbb{R}the real numbers\mathbb{R}: the real numbers


\mathbb{C}the complex numbers\mathbb{C}: the complex numbers

Caution: Some people (roughly half of the world?) call the set \{1, 2, 3, 4, \ldots \} the natural numbers. We are not among them.  We take the pythonic approach that assumes that starting with zero is more natural than starting at one.

